1. Introduction-0.0.0
This is the requirements document for a DNS name server and aims to-0.0.0
document the goals and non-goals of the project.  The DNS (the Domain-0.0.0
Name System) is a global, replicated database that uses a hierarchical-0.0.0
structure for queries.-0.0.0
Data in the DNS is stored in Resource Record sets (RR sets), and has a-0.0.0
time to live (TTL).  During this time the data can be cached.  It is-0.0.0
thus useful to cache data to speed up future lookups.  A server that-0.0.0
looks up data in the DNS for clients and caches previous answers to-0.0.0
speed up processing is called a caching, recursive nameserver.-0.0.0
This project aims to develop such a nameserver in modular components, so-0.0.0
that also DNSSEC (secure DNS) validation and stub-resolvers (that do not-0.0.0
run as a server, but a linked into an application) are easily possible.-0.0.0
The main components are the Validator that validates the security-0.0.0
fingerprints on data sets, the Iterator that sends queries to the-0.0.0
hierarchical DNS servers that own the data and the Cache that stores-0.0.0
data from previous queries.  The networking and query management code-0.0.0
then interface with the modules to perform the necessary processing.-0.0.0
In Section 2 the origins of the Unbound project are documented. Section-0.0.0
3 lists the goals, while Section 4 lists the explicit non-goals of the-0.0.0
project. Section 5 discusses choices made during development.-0.0.0
2. History-0.0.0
The unbound resolver project started by Bill Manning, David Blacka, and-0.0.0
Matt Larson (from the University of California and from Verisign), that-0.0.0
created a Java based prototype resolver called Unbound.  The basic-0.0.0
design decisions of clean modules was executed.-0.0.0
The Java prototype worked very well, with contributions from Geoff-0.0.0
Sisson and Roy Arends from Nominet.  Around 2006 the idea came to create-0.0.0
a full-fledged C implementation ready for deployed use.  NLnet Labs-0.0.0
volunteered to write this implementation.-0.0.0
o A validating recursive DNS resolver.-0.0.0
o Code diversity in the DNS resolver monoculture.-0.0.0
o Drop-in replacement for BIND apart from config.-0.0.0
o DNSSEC support.-0.0.0
o Fully RFC compliant.-0.0.0
o High performance-0.0.0
o Used as-0.0.0

duplicates, but when presented with duplicates on the wire from the-0.0.0
authoritative servers, does not perform duplicate removal.-0.0.0

rrsig and any, because of special rrsig processing in the msgparser.-0.0.0
o The harden-glue feature, when yes all out of zone glue is deleted, when-0.0.0
no out of zone glue is used for further resolving, is more complicated-0.0.0
than that, see below.-0.0.0
Main points:-0.0.0
Not all glue is let through (despite the name of the option). Only glue-0.0.0
which is present in a delegation, of type A and AAAA, where the name is-0.0.0
present in the NS record in the authority section is let through.-0.0.0
The glue that is let through is stored in the cache (marked as 'from the-0.0.0
additional section'). And will then be used for sending queries to. It-0.0.0
will not be present in the reply to the client (if RD is off).-0.0.0
A direct query for that name will attempt to get a msg into the message-0.0.0
cache. Since A and AAAA queries are not synthesized by the unbound cache,-0.0.0
this query will be (eventually) sent to the authoritative server and its-0.0.0
answer will be put in the cache, marked as 'from the answer section' and-0.0.0
thus remove the 'from the additional section' data, and this record is-0.0.0
returned to the client.-0.0.0
The message has a TTL smaller or equal to the TTL of the answer RR.-0.0.0
If the cache memory is low-0.0.0
RR may be inserted, within the message TTL time, and thus return the-0.0.0
spoofed glue to a client. When the message expires, it is refetched and-0.0.0
the cached RR is updated with the correct content.-0.0.0
The server can be spoofed by getting it to visit a especially prepared-0.0.0
domain. This domain then inserts an address for another authoritative-0.0.0
server into the cache, when visiting that other domain, this address may-0.0.0
then be used to send queries to. And fake answers may be returned.-0.0.0
If the other domain is signed by DNSSEC, the fakes will be detected.-0.0.0

disabled. Disabling the feature leads to possible better performance-0.0.0
as more glue is present for the recursive service to use. The feature-0.0.0
is implemented so as to minimise the security risk, while trying to-0.0.0

o The method by which dnssec-lameness is detected is not secure. DNSSEC lame-0.0.0
is when a server has the zone in question, but lacks dnssec data, such as-0.0.0

to create a false sense of dnssec-lameness in the child, or a false sense-0.0.0
or dnssec-non-lameness in the child. The first results in the server marked-0.0.0
lame, and not used for 900 seconds, and the second will result in a-0.0.0
validator failure (SERVFAIL again), when the query is validated later on.-0.0.0

of denial of service. I.e. a completely different NS set could be returned,-0.0.0
or the information withheld. All of these alterations can be caught by-0.0.0
the validator if the parent is signed, and result in 900 seconds bogus.-0.0.0

before the validator will properly verify the messages.-0.0.0

parent, dnssec-lameness detection enables. This delivers dnssec to our-0.0.0
clients when possible (for client validators).-0.0.0

a server that serves both a parent and child zone, where-0.0.0
parent is signed, but child is not. The server must not be marked-0.0.0
lame for the parent zone, because the child answer is not signed.-0.0.0

servers lame. dnssec-lameness is a config error and deserves the trouble.-0.0.0

lame. The zone is identified by SOA or NS RRsets in the answer/auth.-0.0.0

from their zone, this covers most delegation-centric zones.-0.0.0

However, some authority features are expected in a recursor. Things like-0.0.0
localhost, reverse lookup for 127.0.0.1, or blocking AS112 traffic.-0.0.0

providers. Limited support is added specifically to address this.-0.0.0

answer section: empty-0.0.0

with attempt at no-DS proof) or a nodata answer with attempt-0.0.0

a0004e968063e457fe400ac69cec77d0e2f5219e: Requirements push.cocoapods.org-0.0.0
- Eloy Durán, eloy.de.enige-0.0.0

The ‘push’ app is a web-service that accepts pod specifications that are to be added to the master spec repo. Its respondibility is to add a ACL layer on who gets to push specs for a certain library, validates the specs, and merges them into the spec repo.-0.0.0
USER STORIES-0.0.0
Push-workflow-0.0.0
As a user I would like to push a specification so I can publish a new library to the master spec repo. --0.0.0
The client should include a serialized version of the specification, because we don’t want to evaluate user-supplied Ruby on the service.-0.0.0
As an owner I would like to push a specification so I can publish an updated library to the master spec repo. --0.0.0
The client should include a serialized version of the specification, because we don’t want to evaluate user-supplied Ruby on the service.-0.0.0
As a maintainer I want to have a GitHub pull-request for each push so I can discuss issues with the submitter and/or merge manually. --0.0.0
Manual merging is only necessary in case of issues with the push-workflow, e.g. Travis not finishing because of network outage.-0.0.0
As a maintainer I want Travis to verify the validity of a pod specification so I can know if the specification is OK to be merged in to the master spec repo. --0.0.0
This is normally done automatically by GitHub by calling the Travis webhook for each pull-request.-0.0.0
As a maintainer I want the push-app to automatically merge the pull-request so I can sit back and enjoy the finer things in life. --0.0.0
Use Travis’ ability to call webhooks after running a build for this.-0.0.0
Access-Control-List-0.0.0
As a user I should be the ‘owner’ of a library when I publish the first version of a library so I can ensure nobody else is allowed to update that library. --0.0.0
As an owner I should be able to mark another user as ‘owner’ so I can delegate control and maintenance over a library to others. --0.0.0
Non-functional-0.0.0
As a developer I should be able to access a database containing information of all available libaries so I can write other useful related web-services.-0.0.0
Specifically, the download-count app, which needs to know if pods being reported to it are actually being tracked by us, or are private/3rd party/-0.0.0
ROLES-0.0.0
User: Someone who interacts with the push-app, but is not yet an ‘owner’.-0.0.0
Owner: Someone who has elevated access for a library and is allowed to push updates for known libraries.-0.0.0
Submitter: Any person who interacts with the push-app, regardless of ‘user’ or ‘owner’ status.-0.0.0
Maintainer: Someone who maintains the master spec repo. (Has git push access.)-0.0.0
Developer: A computer-whisperer.-0.0.0
DEFINITIONS-0.0.0
Push: The action of submitting a pod specification to the push-app.-0.0.0
Push-app: This web-service application.-0.0.0
Push-workflow: All the actions that need to be performed when pushing a specification.-0.0.0
